did.abstract: The position of Associate Dean of Research and Operations was established within the School of Business administration in 1984 with the appointment of George W. Hettenhouse. Collection consists of administrative files, correspondence, grants, and program files that represent the activities of the Associate Dean of Research and Operations and the Kelley School of Business.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Select files are closed to researchers at this time, primarily due to the existence of Social Security Numbers which were not extracted during processing. Access may be granted to researchers upon review of the files by the Archivist.
At this time, all records relating to development, fundraising, and the IU Foundation are closed to researchers. Contact the IU Archivist for further information.
Restricted files are listed where they fall in the intellectual organization but are physically located in Boxes 18 and 19.
Advance notice required for access to collection.

bioghist.head: Administrative History
bioghist.p: The Kelley School of Business at Indiana University was established in 1920 as the School of Commerce and Finance and has grown to the large and well-respected school it is today.

In 1984, three associate deans were added to the Business School administration: an associate dean of academics, an associate dean of research and operations, and an associate dean of professional programs. The Associate Dean of Research and Operations was responsible for relations with international business programs, strategic planning, research centers, grant proposals, review committees, budget management, and general administration within the School. George W. Hettenhouse was the first to serve in this position, followed by Robert C. Klemkosky, and finally, R. Jeffery Green.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Collection is organized into four series: Administration, Correspondence, Grants, and Program files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: This collection contains records of the Kelley School Associate Deans of Research and Operations during their tenure from 1984 to 2000. They were created and collected by the three men to hold this position: George W. Hettenhouse, Robert C. Klemkosky, and R. Jeffery Green. The records are organized into four series: Administration, Correspondence, Grants, and Program files.

The Administrative series spans the years 1946-2000 (7.5 cubic feet) and contains information regarding budgets, business placement, faculty, and strategic planning. Prominent in this series are records relating to the budget, teaching - evaluations and excellence, and to the activities of the Board of Governors.

The Correspondence series spans the period from 1992 to 1998 (1 cubic foot) and focuses on outgoing and incoming correspondence related to subject or topics such as faculty placement, grants, committees, and proposed budgets. Several folders contain correspondence with Robert C. Klemkosky on topics such as investment management firms, Business Horizons, international trips, and student projects.

The Grants series spans the years 1983-2000 (3 cubic feet) and contains files relating to funding proposals to support the mission and programs of the Kelley School of Business. Prominent are records relating to Center for International Business Education and Research (CIBER), grants (used to support the doctoral, masters and undergraduate programs), research and placement, as well as grants supporting faculty research.

The Grants series spans the years 1983-2000 (3 cubic feet) and contains files relating to funding proposals to support the mission and programs of the Kelley School of Business. Prominent are records relating to Center for International Business Education and Research (CIBER), grants (used to support the doctoral, masters and undergraduate programs), research and placement, as well as grants supporting faculty research.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: An architectural drawing found in the Showers Building, 1989-1995 folder was removed and placed in the Architectural Drawings collection.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: [Item], Kelley School of Business Associate Dean for Research and Operations records, Collection C509, Indiana University Archives, Bloomington.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: Transferred from the Kelley School of Business, 2013.

appraisal.head: Appraisal
appraisal.p: There is a great deal of information relating to development in this collection. All IU Foundation "Contact" updates relating to donors were removed and shredded. Other files, containing correspondence and annual-type reports were retained but are closed to researchers at this time.
A large number of files holding faculty equipment requests were removed and discarded.
